\section{Random effects}{

Variance components render as a subordinate \verb{Random effects} block of
rows: one row per standard deviation, correlation, and the residual, each
with its estimate, SE, and CI (\code{merDeriv} for lme4; native
\code{confint()} / \code{intervals()} for glmmTMB / nlme; identical random
structures from different engines align on the same rows). \code{re_scale}
switches between the SD (default) and variance scales; \code{re_columns}
controls which cells display.

There is deliberately \strong{no per-row p-value} on variance components: the
null sigma = 0 sits on the boundary of the parameter space, where a Wald
test is invalid (Self & Liang 1987), and no reporting guideline requests
one. The significance signal for the random part is the footer's
likelihood-ratio test against the no-random-effects model, with the
boundary-corrected chi-bar-squared p-value (Stram & Lee 1994) -- the same
line Stata's \code{mixed} prints. \code{re_test = "lrt"} / \code{"rlrt"} adds an opt-in
per-term test (LR vs the reduced random structure with the
chi-bar-squared reference, or \code{RLRsim}'s exact restricted LRT) -- never a
Wald z.
}

\section{Fit statistics}{

Defaults: \code{nobs}, \code{n_groups}, \code{icc}, \code{r2_marginal}, \code{r2_conditional},
\code{AIC}, \code{BIC}. The Nakagawa marginal / conditional R-squared are
cross-validated against \code{performance::r2_nakagawa()}; the ICC row is
dropped automatically when the ICC is not defined (random slopes,
crossed factors, families without a link-scale variance).
}

\section{Robust variance}{

\verb{CR*} cluster-robust via \pkg{clubSandwich} (with Satterthwaite df for
\code{lmer}). For \code{glmmTMB} the CR backend covers the conditional fixed
effects only; component rows stay model-based, disclosed in the footer.
\verb{HC*} is refused (a single-level concept).
}

